Step 1: Calculate Return on Equity (ROE)

• Determine beginning and ending owner's equity from the balance sheet.
  Beginning Owner's Equity = 13,000,000.00
  Ending Owner's Equity = 11,330,150.23  
• Compute the average owner's equity:
  Average Owner's Equity = (13,000,000.00 + 11,330,150.23) / 2 = 12,165,075.115  
• Identify the net profit from the income statement:
  Net Profit = –1,669,849.77  
• Now, ROE = (Net Profit / Average Owner's Equity) × 100  
  ROE = (–1,669,849.77 / 12,165,075.115) × 100 ≈ –13.72%

Step 2: Calculate Debt to Asset Ratio

• Total liabilities at year-end can be derived by subtracting owner's equity from total liabilities and owner's equity:
  Total Liabilities = 14,066,175.95 – 11,330,150.23 = 2,736,025.72  
• Total Assets at year-end = 14,066,175.95  
• Debt to Asset Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Assets  
  = 2,736,025.72 / 14,066,175.95 ≈ 0.1946  
  Rounded, this is approximately 0.19

Step 3: Calculate Gross Profit Margin

• From the income statement:
  Gross Profit = 1,340,513.79  
  Total Revenue = 6,920,513.79  
• Gross Profit Margin = (Gross Profit / Total Revenue) × 100  
  = (1,340,513.79 / 6,920,513.79) × 100 ≈ 19.37%

Thus, the results are:

{
  "solution": {
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "-13.72%",
    "Debt to Asset Ratio": "0.19",
    "Gross Profit Margin": "19.37%"
  }
}
